messages.content: fotd 1: one of the most famous ritual suicides in history happened right in our backyard by the heaven's gate in rancho santa fe. their leaders were thought to be literally superhuman until one of them fucking died. so they twisted the narrative and all of killed themselves. talk about conformity huh

fotd 2: the french philosopher/author/critic denis diderot is best known for writing the encyclopédie, a general encyclopedia encompassing enlightenment thoughts. something more interesting is that he wrote the novel "the indiscreet jewels" where a sultan owns a magic ring that makes women's genitals talk. how useful huh

fotd 3: there are many historical inaccuracies surrounding napoleon and his rule. one of the most famous inaccuracies was that he was really fucking short. this fallacy was due to a 5-unit difference between english and french systems of measurement and was perpetuated in political cartoons such as "little boney in a strong fit." imagine being one of the most successful and imposing leaders in the history of mankind but becoming the laughingstock of the world since some idiot couldnt do math and thought you were a midget. kinda feelsbad huh

fotd 4: one of the most famous series of paintings in the latter half of the 20th century was the helga pictures by american painter andrew wyeth. though he was married, wyeth painted over 240 portraits of german model helga testorf over the course of fourteen years. many of these paintings were explicit and nude, and helga was even the guest of honor at wyeth's 90th birthday. although wyeth denied an intimate relationship with helga, it was so fucking obvious smth was up (names of paintings include "lovers" and "ON HER KNEES"). kinda sus huh

fotd 5: one of the most depressing pieces of literature i have read is the short story "tits-up in a ditch" by annie proulx. the protagonist dakota was abandoned by her mother as a baby. after getting older, dakota goes on to find herself pregnant, married, and abandoned by her husband sash (who went to fight in the iraq war). she then leaves her baby and joins the army to also fight in the iraq war. upon losing an arm while fighting, she comes home to a dead baby and a comatose sash with both legs blown off and half his head gone. god really said "fuck dakota" huh

fotd 6: for two months from march 18th, 1871 to may 28, 1871, france was a communist nation under the paris commune. occuring right after napoleon iii's capture and france's defeat in the franco-prussian war, angry mobs of workers stormed the streets of paris and took control of the government. my favorite part of the paris commune is the pétroleuses, women that went fucking king kong and burned down basically all of paris. girl power huh

fotd 7: a poem i really like is "richard cory" by edwin arlington robinson. it speaks of a man named richard cory who is the envy of everyone in town: "he was a gentleman from sole to crown/Clean favored, and imperially slim." he was rich, composed, and the man that everyone wanted to be, but "one calm summer night,/[he] went home and put a bullet through his head." though perfect on the outside, who knows all the horrible things richard was going through? we should take this as a lesson -- go check up on someone and make sure they're doing okay before something bad does happen. love y'all ❤️

fotd 8: one of the most famous rulers in the history of india was ashoka the great of the mauryan empire. in history classes we learn of how he became a benevolent ruler and a pacifist after his conquest of kalinga, but many buddhist texts say otherwise, calling him "candashoka" (ashoka the cruel). a prime example of this was ashoka's hell, a torture chamber ashoka had constructed in his capital pataliputra. on the outside it looked like a palace with all the external accoutrements of decadence and pleasure, but entry into the palace revealed only pain. the torture devices within the palace were so horrible that many were sure that ashoka had taken a voyage into hell to perfectly recreate it. how scary huh (on that note, happy halloween y'all!)

fotd 9: just like many other asian countries, korea has a mythological explanation for how its state was founded. it all began when the son of the lord of heaven, hwanung, founded the sinsi (city of god) on baekdu mountain to communicate with the humans and teach them how to be good. one day, a tiger and a bear came to hwanung asking to become human. hwanung gave both of them twenty cloves of garlic and a bundle of mugwort, ordering them to only sustain themselves on this food and remain out of sunlight for 100 days. the tiger gave up very soon, but the bear persevered through the 100 days and became a woman; however, she lacked a husband or a child and became sad. upon praying under a tree for a long time, hwanung became pleased and took her as his wife. soon they gave birth to emperor dangun, the founder of the gojoseon dynasty, who began his rule in 2333 BCE (according to the dongguk tonggam).
